snippet.textDisplay:
WONDERFUL PRESENTATION!!!! I LOVE THIS!!! Just a couple things I've shared with it when I share it as some info is not accurate to my understanding:


Virus can live on surfaces, esp metal for up to 9 days in perfect conditions. https://www.journalofhospitalinfection.com/article/S0195-6701(20)30046-3/fulltext


The cruise ship found INACTIVE virus at 17 days. The novel virus' RNA was found - not necessarily live virus... https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-found-on-diamond-princess-surfaces-17-days-later-2020-3


SOAP is always best for cleaning... it breaks the virus from working. https://youtu.be/-LKVUarhtvE?t=22
I personally let items that CAN, sit for 10 days on the porch until use.



He NEEDS A PARTNER to grab with a CLEAN HAND, like one that didn't open the suspect cardboard box... to grab that cereal bag. {though, yep, his demo is GREAT!!!}


EVERY TIME he touches the disinfectant should be with a CLEAN hand, not one that touched the bag.


I'd have left those chips on the porch... don't want to eat all the good chips first!!


Nice job on the fruit - he notes no soap as a correction but I'd use vinegar I think and let them sit a day or two.


The Take out tips look good. Foraging for Food!! Love it!!! :D [most viruses cannot survive above 170-180 degrees - sorry I couldn't find a link to a good piece on this.]


Thanks for the great work on this FINELY DONE video, Jeffrey. And Thank YOU for being on the front lines of the pandemic.

Great ideas Doctor! Thank you for helping get the word out. I like your technique for the produce and will adapt this into my own practice at home. As a person who performs sterile tech procedures myself, I would like to emphasize that "sterile" techniques are a practice and not 100%, but if they were not practiced, our surgical / procedural infection rates would be medieval.


Our culture is changing, and we all now have a renewed respect for viral disease. Do not be too proud to be careful! Let's all relax, and change our habits for the better of our loved ones and society in general. If you second guess being careful with your groceries you must ask yourself "Did I put on a seat-belt before I drove to the store"?

snippet.textDisplay: I read the full CDC report about detecting coronavirus on a cruise ship after 17 days.  It is VERY important to note that the detection method used did NOT detect "active" or "live" virus.  The assay they used detects only viral RNA - in fact, less than 500 bases of the genomic RNA (which is 30,000 bases long) is sufficient for a positive test.  RNA is unstable, but fragments could remain for several weeks. Coronavirus dies when it dries - it can survive longer on wet produce than on a cardboard box.
snippet.textOriginal: I read the full CDC report about detecting coronavirus on a cruise ship after 17 days.  It is VERY important to note that the detection method used did NOT detect "active" or "live" virus.  The assay they used detects only viral RNA - in fact, less than 500 bases of the genomic RNA (which is 30,000 bases long) is sufficient for a positive test.  RNA is unstable, but fragments could remain for several weeks. Coronavirus dies when it dries - it can survive longer on wet produce than on a cardboard box.

I also have other produce stored on a cooler in my car trunk or garage when I need to restock in my home after the other has been eaten.

snippet.textDisplay:
The US Food & Drug Administration’s (FDA) guidelines on food safety and coronavirus do not include the disinfecting of perishable and non-perishable grocery items. In a statement on March 24, Frank Yiannas, the FDA’s deputy commissioner for food policy and response, said, “There is no evidence of human or animal food or food packaging being associated with transmission of the coronavirus that causes Covid-19.” (The FDA notes that “it may be possible that a person can get Covid-19 by touching a surface or object that has the virus on it and then touching their mouth, nose, or possibly their eyes, but this is not thought to be the main way the virus spreads.”)


Don Schaffner, a professor of food microbiology at Rutgers School of Environmental and Biological Sciences and host of the podcasts Food Safety Talk and Risky or Not?, echoed the FDA’s recommendations regarding food handling. “I am not recommending disinfecting your groceries. This seems like being overly cautious. We don’t know of any cases of Covid-19 transmitted by food, nor of any cases transmitted by food packaging.”


Schaffner does, however, recommend washing your hands after returning from the grocery store, after putting groceries away, and before eating.

Don Schaffner, a professor of food microbiology at Rutgers School of Environmental and Biological Sciences and host of the podcasts Food Safety Talk and Risky or Not?, echoed the FDA’s recommendations regarding food handling. “I am not recommending disinfecting your groceries.
